04610nam a22006615i 9781575064451DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a2016045033  a97815750644517 a10.1515/97815750644512doi  a(DE-B1597)606822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA00aBS1430.6.B5bB37 2016 4aBS1430.6.B5bB37 2016 7aREL0062102bisacsh04a221.6012231 aBarker, Kit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImprecation as Divine Discourse :bSpeech Act Theory, Dual Authorship, and Theological Interpretation /cKit Barker. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJournal of Theological Interpretation Supplements ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. In Pursuit of Theological Interpretation -- tChapter 1. Speech Act Theory -- tChapter 2. Dual Authorship -- tChapter 3. Speech Act Theory, Dual Authorship and Canonical Hermeneutics -- tPart II. Theological Interpretation and the Psalter -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 4. The Divine Illocutions of the Psalter in Its Old Testament Context -- tChapter 5. The Theological Interpretation of Imprecatory Psalms -- tChapter 6. A Theological Interpretation of Psalm 137 -- tChapter 7. A Theological Interpretation Of Psalm 69 -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Authors and Subject -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChristian readers of the Hebrew Bible are often faced with a troubling tension. On the one hand, they are convinced that this ancient text is relevant today, yet on the other, they remain perplexed at how this can be so, particularly when parts of it appear to condone violence. Barker's volume seeks to address this tension in two parts: (1) by defending a particular form of theological interpretation and (2) by applying this interpretive method to the imprecatory psalms.Barker suggests that the goal of theological interpretation is to discover God's voice in the text. While he recognizes that this goal could encourage a subjective methodology, Barker offers a hermeneutic that clearly locates God's voice in the text of Scripture. Utilizing the resources of speech act theory, Barker notes that texts convey meaning at a number of literary levels and that God's appropriation of speech acts at these levels is not necessarily uniform for each genre. He also discusses how the Christian canon alters the context of these ancient speech acts, both reshaping and enabling their continued function as divine discourse. In order to demonstrate the usefulness of this hermeneutic, Barker offers theological interpretations of Psalms 69 and 137. He demonstrates how christological fulfilment and the call to forgive one's enemies are determinative for a theological interpretation of these troubling psalms, concluding that they continue to form an essential part of God's voice that must not be ignored.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBlessing and cursing in the Bible. 0aSpeech acts (Linguistics)xReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / Old Testament.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575064451zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575064451423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781575064451/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK